data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages. MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(list)` | Better failure message if 0 or 2+ match |

If the admin check is its own concern, `Assert.ContainsSingle` is cleanest:

```csharp
var admins = users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin").ToList();
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(admins); // fails with clear message if != 1
Assert.IsTrue(admin.IsActive);
```

These APIs require **MSTest 3.8+** (`<PackageReference Include="MSTest" Version="3.8.2" />` or `MSTest.Sdk`).
